    slug: "holnak-toofan-qissa-syedna-nooh-silsila-qasas-ul-anbiya-330",
    description: `Holnak Toofan (Qissa Syedna Nooh) Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya 3/30 is the third volume in the acclaimed Urdu-language Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya series, focusing on the story of Prophet Nooh (Noah), peace be upon him, and the Great Flood (Toofan-e-Nooh) that Allah sent as a punishment upon the disbelievers of his time. The title "Holnak Toofan" translates to "The Terrible Flood," referring to the catastrophic deluge that destroyed the civilization of Nooh's people while Nooh and the believers were saved in the Ark. This volume is part of a thirty-book series that systematically narrates the stories of all the prophets mentioned in the Quran, and it is one of the most popular volumes in the collection due to the dramatic and universally recognizable nature of the flood narrative.

The book narrates the story of Prophet Nooh from the Quranic accounts found in multiple surahs, including Surah Nuh, Surah Al-A'raf, Surah Hud, Surah Al-Anbiya, and Surah Ash-Shu'ara, supplemented by authentic hadith narrations and classical Islamic exegesis. Prophet Nooh is described in the Quran as having the longest prophetic mission of any messenger, spending approximately 950 years calling his people to the worship of Allah alone. The book details Nooh's patient and tireless da'wah efforts, describing how he used every possible method to convince his people to abandon idol worship, including public preaching, private counseling, and showing them the signs of Allah's power in creation. Despite these sustained efforts spanning nearly a millennium, only a small handful of people believed in his message, including some members of his own family.

The narrative reaches its climax with the building of the Ark and the coming of the Great Flood. The book describes how Allah commanded Nooh to build a massive vessel under divine guidance, even though there was no body of water nearby at the time, and how the disbelievers mocked and ridiculed Nooh for constructing a ship on dry land. When the flood came, the book recounts how the earth opened up and water gushed forth from the ground while rain poured from the sky in unprecedented quantities, submerging everything except the Ark and those who had taken refuge within it. The poignant moment when Nooh's own son refused to board the Ark and was drowned is described with the emotional depth it deserves, drawing on the Quranic dialogue between Nooh and his son. The book concludes with the aftermath of the flood, the grounding of the Ark on Mount Judi, and the establishment of Nooh and the believers as the new beginning for humanity. The spiritual lessons of steadfastness in da'wah, patience in the face of ridicule, trust in Allah's plan, and the consequences of rejecting divine guidance are thoroughly explored throughout the narrative, making this volume an educational and inspiring read for Urdu-speaking Muslims of all ages.`,
