    slug: "hospital-mein-mareez-aur-tabeeb-kai-sath",
    description: `Hospital Mein Mareez Aur Tabeeb Kai Sath is an Urdu-language Islamic book that addresses the important but often overlooked topic of Islamic etiquette and rulings related to visiting the sick and the relationship between patients and medical professionals in a hospital setting. The title translates roughly to "In the Hospital: With the Patient and the Doctor," and the book provides a comprehensive guide based on the Quran, the authentic Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the opinions of classical and contemporary Islamic scholars regarding the rights, responsibilities, and proper conduct of everyone involved in the healthcare environment. The book fills a significant gap in Urdu Islamic literature, as while there are many books on general Islamic manners, few address the specific context of modern hospitals and medical treatment in such a detailed and practical manner.

The book is organized into several major sections, each addressing a different aspect of the patient-doctor relationship and the hospital visit. The first section covers the Islamic rulings on seeking medical treatment, establishing the principle that Islam encourages Muslims to seek cures for their illnesses and does not提倡 reliance on spiritual means alone to the exclusion of medical intervention. It draws upon the well-known hadith in which the Prophet (peace be upon him) said, "Allah has not sent down any disease except that He has also sent down the cure" (Sahih al-Bukhari), and discusses the Islamic perspective on various types of medical treatment, including conventional medicine, surgery, and the use of medication. The second section addresses the etiquette of visiting the sick, covering topics such as the virtues of visiting the sick, the recommended duas to make for the patient, the appropriate length and timing of visits, what to say and what to avoid saying, and the special rulings for visiting non-Muslim patients or patients of the opposite gender.

The third section discusses the rights of the patient in Islam, including the right to receive treatment, the right to informed consent, the right to privacy and dignity, and the right to refuse treatment under certain circumstances. The fourth section addresses the responsibilities of the doctor and healthcare provider from an Islamic perspective, including the obligation to provide the best possible care, the prohibition of negligence or harm, the ethics of medical research, and the Islamic rulings on various medical procedures and ethical dilemmas such as euthanasia, organ donation, and abortion. The book also covers practical topics such as the Islamic etiquette of being admitted to a hospital, how to maintain one's religious obligations (such as prayer and fasting) while ill or hospitalized, and how to cope with serious illness from an Islamic spiritual perspective. The Urdu prose is clear and practical, with references to the original sources for every ruling, making this book a valuable reference for patients, doctors, nurses, hospital chaplains, and anyone who visits the sick or works in a healthcare environment.`,
